**Summary of previous steps:** We need to find prime numbers \( p \) such that \( p \equiv 3 \pmod{n} \) for every integer \( n < 15 \). The primes \( 2, 3, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, \) and \( 23 \) have been tested. None satisfy the condition for all \( n \), failing at least one, such as \( 23 \equiv 1 \pmod{2} \) or \( 23 \equiv 2 \pmod{3} \).

